<h2>HVAC Systems in Oregon</h2>
<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Oregon's climate presents unique challenges and opportunities for HVAC system design and operation. The state's marine climate, characterized by mild, wet winters and warm, dry summers, creates heating demands from October through April and cooling needs primarily from June through September. Winter temperatures in the Willamette Valley typically range from 35-50¬∞F, while summer temperatures commonly reach 75-85¬∞F with occasional heat waves exceeding 90¬∞F. This moderate climate makes heat pump technology particularly attractive, as these systems can efficiently provide both heating and cooling functions year-round.</p>

<p>Humidity levels in Oregon vary significantly by season, with winter humidity often reaching 80-90% due to frequent precipitation, while summer humidity can drop to 30-40% during dry periods. This variation requires HVAC systems capable of managing both moisture removal during humid periods and maintaining comfort during dry conditions. Traditional forced-air systems with proper humidity control, ductless mini-split systems, and modern heat pump installations all perform well in Oregon's climate when properly sized and configured.</p>

<p>The state's geographical diversity also creates microclimates that affect HVAC requirements. Coastal areas experience more moderate temperatures year-round but higher humidity and salt air exposure that can impact equipment longevity. Eastern Oregon faces more extreme temperature variations with colder winters and hotter summers, requiring more robust heating and cooling capabilities. High-altitude areas in the Cascades and other mountain ranges require specialized considerations for equipment sizing and cold-weather performance.</p>

