<h2>Oregon Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>Oregon offers some of the most comprehensive incentive programs in the nation for both solar panel installations and HVAC system upgrades. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) allows homeowners to deduct 30% of the cost of installing a solar energy system from their federal taxes, with no cap on the credit amount. This credit is available through 2032, though it will decrease to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034 before expiring for residential installations. The ITC applies to the total system cost including equipment, installation, and associated electrical work.</p>

<p>Oregon's state-level solar incentives include rebates up to \$5,000 through the Solar Within Reach program, specifically designed to make solar accessible to low- and moderate-income households. Additionally, the state offers property tax exemptions for solar installations, meaning the added value from solar panels won't increase property tax assessments. The Business Energy Tax Credit provides additional incentives for commercial solar installations, and Oregon's net metering policies ensure that excess solar production receives full retail credit.</p>

<p>Portland General Electric and Pacific Power, Oregon's major utilities, provide additional rebates and incentives for both solar and HVAC systems. PGE's renewable energy incentives include rebates for battery storage systems when paired with solar installations, while their Smart Grid Test Bed program offers additional incentives for advanced energy management systems. For HVAC systems, both utilities offer substantial rebates for high-efficiency heat pumps, ranging from \$300-1,500 depending on system efficiency and type. Energy Trust of Oregon, funded by utility customers, provides additional rebates for ductless heat pumps (\$300-800), central air conditioning systems (\$200-400), and smart thermostats (\$50-100).</p>

<p>The combination of federal, state, and utility incentives can reduce the total cost of solar installations by 40-50% and HVAC system upgrades by 15-25%. Low-income households may qualify for additional programs through the Oregon Department of Energy's weatherization assistance programs, which can provide grants rather than rebates for energy efficiency improvements. Many Oregon cities and counties also offer expedited permitting for solar installations and additional rebates for energy efficiency improvements, making it important to research local programs in addition to state and federal incentives.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6 my-6">
