  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">What SEER rating is recommended for Oregon?</h3>
    <p>For Oregon's climate, HVAC systems with SEER ratings between 14-18 provide the optimal balance of efficiency and cost-effectiveness. While higher SEER ratings offer greater efficiency, the moderate cooling demands in most of Oregon mean that SEER ratings above 18 may not provide sufficient additional savings to justify their higher costs. Heat pump systems should have HSPF (Heating Seasonal Performance Factor) ratings of at least 8.5 for optimal winter heating efficiency. For ductless mini-split systems, SEER ratings of 16-20 are common and provide excellent efficiency for both heating and cooling applications.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Do solar panels work during Oregon's cloudy weather?</h3>
    <p>Yes, solar panels continue to generate electricity during cloudy weather, though at reduced capacity. Modern photovoltaic panels can produce 10-30% of their peak output even on overcast days by capturing diffuse sunlight that penetrates cloud cover. Oregon's solar systems are designed with this weather pattern in mind, and annual production calculations account for seasonal variations. Net metering policies allow Oregon homeowners to bank excess electricity produced during sunny periods to offset consumption during cloudy periods, effectively using the electrical grid as storage. Many Oregon solar installations actually perform better than expected due to the state's cool temperatures, which improve solar panel efficiency compared to hotter climates.</p`;
